      ["What is double-entry accounting?", "A system where every transaction affects at least two accounts with equal debits and credits."],
      ["Scenario: Company buys $500 equipment for cash. How is this recorded?", "Debit Equipment $500, Credit Cash $500."],
      ["What is a debit?", "An entry on the left side of an account that increases assets or expenses and decreases liabilities or equity."],
      ["What is a credit?", "An entry on the right side of an account that increases liabilities, equity, or revenue and decreases assets or expenses."],
      ["Scenario: Company receives $1,000 from a customer on account. Which accounts are debited and credited?", "Debit Cash $1,000, Credit Accounts Receivable $1,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $200 for utilities. How to record?", "Debit Utilities Expense $200, Credit Cash $200."],
      ["What is the main purpose of double-entry accounting?", "To ensure the accounting equation (Assets = Liabilities + Equity) remains balanced."],
      ["Scenario: Owner invests $2,000 cash into the business. How is it recorded?", "Debit Cash $2,000, Credit Owner’s Capital $2,000."],
      ["Which accounts normally have debit balances?", "Assets and expenses usually have debit balances."],
      ["Which accounts normally have credit balances?", "Liabilities, owner’s equity, and revenue usually have credit balances."],
      ["Scenario: Company borrows $5,000 from a bank. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $5,000, Credit Notes Payable $5,000."],
      ["What happens if debits and credits are not equal?", "The books are out of balance, indicating an error in recording."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $600 for prepaid insurance. Record the entry.", "Debit Prepaid Insurance $600, Credit Cash $600."],
      ["Why is double-entry accounting considered more accurate than single-entry?", "It tracks both sides of every transaction, reducing errors and providing a complete picture."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $1,200 revenue on account. Record the entry.", "Debit Accounts Receivable $1,200, Credit Sales Revenue $1,200."],
      ["What type of account is increased with a debit?", "Asset or expense accounts increase with a debit."],
      ["What type of account is increased with a credit?", "Liability, equity, or revenue accounts increase with a credit."],
      ["Scenario: Owner withdraws $500 cash. How is this recorded?", "Debit Owner’s Drawing $500, Credit Cash $500."],
      ["What is the normal balance of an asset account?", "Debit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of a liability account?", "Credit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of an expense account?", "Debit."],
      ["What is the normal balance of a revenue account?", "Credit."],
      ["Scenario: Business purchases inventory on credit for $800. Record the transaction.", "Debit Inventory $800, Credit Accounts Payable $800."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $300 on account. Record the transaction.", "Debit Accounts Payable $300, Credit Cash $300."],
      ["Why must every transaction have at least one debit and one credit?", "To maintain the accounting equation and ensure accurate financial records."],
      ["Scenario: Business receives $1,000 from a customer in advance. How to record?", "Debit Cash $1,000, Credit Unearned Revenue $1,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business records $400 depreciation. How to record?", "Debit Depreciation Expense $400, Credit Accumulated Depreciation $400."],
      ["Scenario: Owner withdraws merchandise for personal use. How to record?", "Debit Owner’s Drawing $value, Credit Inventory $value."],
      ["What does it mean when a transaction is 'balanced'?", "Total debits equal total credits."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $100 for office supplies. How to record?", "Debit Office Supplies Expense $100, Credit Cash $100."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $500 interest revenue. How is it recorded?", "Debit Cash $500, Credit Interest Revenue $500."],
      ["What is the effect of a debit on owner’s equity?", "It decreases owner’s equity through expenses or withdrawals."],
      ["What is the effect of a credit on owner’s equity?", "It increases owner’s equity through capital contributions or revenues."],
      ["Scenario: Company issues $2,000 in common stock for cash. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $2,000, Credit Common Stock $2,000."],
      ["Scenario: Business pays $150 for rent. Record the entry.", "Debit Rent Expense $150, Credit Cash $150."],
      ["Scenario: Company collects $700 from a customer on account. Record the transaction.", "Debit Cash $700, Credit Accounts Receivable $700."]
