      ["What is an income statement?", "A financial statement showing a company’s revenues, expenses, and net income over a period of time."],
      ["What is the main purpose of an income statement?", "To measure profitability and financial performance of a business during a specific period."],
      ["Scenario: Company earned $50,000 in revenue and had $30,000 in expenses. Net income?", "$20,000."],
      ["What are revenues?", "Amounts earned from selling goods or services."],
      ["Scenario: Business sells $5,000 in products. How is it recorded on the income statement?", "As $5,000 revenue."],
      ["What are expenses?", "Costs incurred to generate revenue, such as rent, salaries, and utilities."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $2,000 in rent. How is it reported?", "As an expense on the income statement."],
      ["What is net income?", "The excess of revenues over expenses, also called profit."],
      ["What is net loss?", "When expenses exceed revenues, resulting in a negative net income."],
      ["Scenario: Revenues $10,000, Expenses $12,000. Net result?", "Net loss of $2,000."],
      ["What is the gross profit?", "Revenue minus cost of goods sold (COGS)."],
      ["Scenario: Revenue $20,000, COGS $12,000. Gross profit?", "$8,000."],
      ["What is the difference between gross profit and net income?", "Gross profit ignores operating and other expenses; net income accounts for all expenses."],
      ["What is the operating income?", "Gross profit minus operating expenses like rent and salaries."],
      ["Scenario: Gross profit $15,000, operating expenses $5,000. Operating income?", "$10,000."],
      ["What are non-operating items?", "Revenues or expenses not related to core business operations, like interest or gains/losses on sales."],
      ["Scenario: Company earns $500 interest income. Where does it appear?", "As a non-operating item on the income statement."],
      ["Why are income statements important for investors?", "They provide insight into profitability and efficiency of the business."],
      ["Scenario: Investor compares net income over three years. Purpose?", "Assess company growth and performance trends."],
      ["What is the time period for an income statement?", "Usually monthly, quarterly, or annually."],
      ["Scenario: A business wants to evaluate last quarter’s performance. Which statement?", "Quarterly income statement."],
      ["How does the income statement link to the balance sheet?", "Net income affects retained earnings on the balance sheet."],
      ["Scenario: Net income $10,000. Balance sheet effect?", "Retained earnings increase by $10,000."],
      ["What is the difference between single-step and multi-step income statements?", "Single-step reports all revenues and expenses in one calculation; multi-step separates operating and non-operating activities."],
      ["Scenario: Company shows gross profit, operating income, and net income. Statement type?", "Multi-step income statement."],
      ["What is earnings per share (EPS)?", "Net income divided by outstanding shares, showing profit per share."],
      ["Scenario: Net income $50,000, 10,000 shares. EPS?", "$5 per share."],
      ["Why is matching principle important for income statements?", "Ensures expenses are recorded in the same period as the related revenues."],
      ["Scenario: Supplies bought in March used in April. When expense recorded?", "April, when revenue is earned, per matching principle."],
      ["What are operating expenses?", "Costs related to running core business operations, like salaries and rent."],
      ["Scenario: Company pays $3,000 in salaries. Income statement entry?", "Operating expense of $3,000."],
      ["What are non-operating gains and losses?", "Items unrelated to main operations, such as selling equipment."],
      ["Scenario: Company sells old equipment for $1,000 more than book value. Entry?", "Non-operating gain of $1,000."],
      ["What is the difference between income statement and statement of cash flows?", "Income statement shows profit; cash flows show actual cash inflows and outflows."],
      ["Scenario: Business reports $5,000 net income but $2,000 depreciation. Income vs cash?", "Net income $5,000, cash flow differs due to non-cash expense."],
      ["Why is an income statement considered a performance measure?", "It shows how well a company generates profit from revenues and controls expenses."],
      ["Scenario: Manager uses income statement to cut costs. Purpose?", "Identify high expenses and improve profitability."]
