      ["What is ownership in business?", "The legal right to control and benefit from a business entity."],
      ["What is a sole proprietorship?", "A business owned by one individual who assumes all profits and liabilities."],
      ["Scenario: Maria runs a bakery alone. Type of ownership?", "Sole proprietorship."],
      ["What is a partnership?", "A business owned by two or more individuals who share profits, losses, and management."],
      ["Scenario: Two friends start a landscaping business together. Type of ownership?", "Partnership."],
      ["What is a corporation?", "A legal entity separate from its owners, with ownership represented by stockholders."],
      ["Scenario: A business sells shares to the public. Type of ownership?", "Corporation."],
      ["What is a limited liability company (LLC)?", "A hybrid business structure providing limited liability protection with flexible taxation."],
      ["Scenario: Owners want liability protection and pass-through taxation. Best choice?", "LLC."],
      ["What is limited liability?", "Owner’s personal assets are protected from business debts and obligations."],
      ["What is unlimited liability?", "Owner is personally responsible for all business debts and legal obligations."],
      ["Scenario: Sole proprietor owes $50,000 business debt. Liability type?", "Unlimited liability."],
      ["What is a shareholder?", "An individual or entity that owns shares of a corporation and may receive dividends."],
      ["Scenario: Investor owns 100 shares of a corporation. What is their role?", "Shareholder."],
      ["Why is ownership structure important?", "It affects liability, taxation, management control, and the ability to raise capital."]
      ,
      ["What is a corporation?", "A legal entity separate from its owners, created under state law and capable of owning assets, incurring liabilities, and entering contracts."],
      ["What is limited liability in a corporation?", "Shareholders are not personally responsible for corporate debts beyond their investment in the company."],
      ["Scenario: A corporation owes $1 million but a shareholder invested $10,000. Liability?", "Shareholder is liable only for $10,000; personal assets are protected."],
      ["What is perpetual existence?", "A corporation continues to exist regardless of ownership changes, death, or sale of shares."],
      ["Scenario: CEO of a corporation retires. Does the company continue?", "Yes, due to perpetual existence."],
      ["What are shareholders?", "Individuals or entities that own stock in a corporation and have voting rights and claim to profits."],
      ["Scenario: Investor owns 500 shares of a corporation. What is their role?", "Shareholder."],
      ["What is the role of a board of directors?", "Elected by shareholders to make major policy decisions and oversee management."],
      ["Scenario: Board approves a merger. Who authorized it?", "Board of directors, acting on behalf of shareholders."],
      ["What is stock?", "Ownership units in a corporation that represent a claim on assets and earnings."],
      ["What is dividend?", "A distribution of profits to shareholders based on the number of shares owned."],
      ["Scenario: Corporation earns profit and pays $2 per share to 1,000 shares. Total dividend?", "$2 × 1,000 = $2,000 paid to shareholders."],
      ["What is the advantage of raising capital through stock?", "Corporations can raise large amounts of money without increasing debt."],
      ["What is double taxation?", "Corporate profits are taxed at the company level and again as shareholder dividends."],
      ["Scenario: Corporation earns $50,000 taxed at 21%, then pays $10,000 dividends. Why taxed twice?", "Profit taxed at corporate level and dividends taxed as shareholder income."]
      ,
      ["What is one major advantage of a corporation?", "Limited liability protects owners’ personal assets from business debts and legal obligations."],
      ["Scenario: Corporation owes $500,000. Shareholder invested $5,000. What is their liability?", "Shareholder is liable only for $5,000, personal assets are protected."],
      ["What is perpetual existence?", "A corporation continues to exist even if owners or management change, ensuring business continuity."],
      ["Scenario: Founder of a corporation dies. Does the company continue?", "Yes, because of perpetual existence."],
      ["What is an advantage of raising capital as a corporation?", "Corporations can issue stock to attract investors and raise large amounts of money."],
      ["What is the disadvantage of double taxation?", "Corporate profits are taxed at the corporate level and dividends taxed again at the shareholder level."],
      ["Scenario: Corporation earns $100,000 profit, pays $20,000 dividend. How is it taxed?", "Profits taxed at corporate rate, and the $20,000 dividends taxed again as shareholder income."],
      ["What is a disadvantage regarding legal requirements?", "Corporations have complex formation procedures, ongoing regulatory filings, and reporting obligations."],
      ["Scenario: Company must file annual reports with the state. What disadvantage is this?", "Administrative complexity and regulatory compliance requirements."],
      ["What is an advantage of transferable ownership?", "Shareholders can buy or sell stock without affecting company operations, making ownership more flexible."],
      ["Scenario: Shareholder sells shares to another investor. Effect on company?", "Company continues operations without disruption, ownership simply transfers."],
      ["What is an advantage related to management structure?", "A corporation can separate ownership from management, allowing professional managers to run operations."],
      ["What is a disadvantage of separation of ownership and control?", "Potential conflicts between managers and shareholders if interests do not align."],
      ["Scenario: Managers prioritize growth over dividends, shareholder unhappy. Which disadvantage?", "Conflict of interest due to separation of ownership and management."],
      ["Why might corporations attract top talent?", "They can offer stock options, competitive benefits, and career advancement opportunities, which smaller businesses may struggle to match."]
      ,
      ["What is a partnership?", "A business owned by two or more individuals who share profits, losses, and management responsibilities."],
      ["Scenario: John and Lisa start a consulting firm together. Type of ownership?", "Partnership."],
      ["What is a general partnership?", "A partnership where all partners share management duties and have unlimited personal liability for business debts."],
      ["What is a limited partnership?", "A partnership with general partners managing the business and limited partners investing capital with liability only up to their investment."],
      ["Scenario: One partner invests money but does not manage. Liability type?", "Limited partnership, limited liability for that partner."],
      ["What is unlimited liability in a partnership?", "Each general partner is personally responsible for the debts and obligations of the business."],
      ["Scenario: Partnership owes $100,000. General partners each contributed $10,000. Who pays?", "General partners are personally responsible for the remaining debt beyond their contributions."],
      ["How are profits and losses shared?", "According to the partnership agreement or, if not specified, equally among partners."],
      ["Scenario: Two partners earn $60,000 total profit, agreement specifies 60/40 split. How much each?", "$36,000 to first partner, $24,000 to second partner."],
      ["What is the role of a partnership agreement?", "Defines profit-sharing, management responsibilities, decision-making, and procedures for adding or removing partners."],
      ["Scenario: New partner joins. What should be updated?", "Partnership agreement to reflect changes in ownership and responsibilities."],
      ["What is a key advantage of a partnership?", "Combines resources, skills, and capital of multiple owners for better management and growth potential."],
      ["What is a key disadvantage of a partnership?", "Partners have personal liability for business debts and conflicts may arise between partners."],
      ["Scenario: Partners disagree on business direction. Risk associated?", "Dispute can harm operations and affect decision-making efficiency."],
      ["Why is trust important in a partnership?", "Partners rely on each other’s integrity and competence, as personal liability and shared decision-making require cooperation."]
      ,

      ["What is a key advantage of partnerships?", "They combine resources, skills, and capital from multiple owners, making the business stronger than a sole proprietorship."],
      ["Scenario: Two partners contribute $50,000 each to start a business. Advantage demonstrated?", "Access to more capital and pooled resources."],
      ["How does shared decision-making benefit a partnership?", "Partners bring diverse skills and perspectives, improving problem-solving and management."],
      ["Scenario: One partner is skilled in marketing, the other in operations. Advantage?", "Complementary skills enhance business performance."],
      ["What is a disadvantage related to liability?", "General partners have unlimited personal liability for business debts and obligations."],
      ["Scenario: Partnership owes $200,000 and cannot pay. Who is responsible?", "Each general partner is personally liable for the debt."],
      ["How can conflicts affect partnerships?", "Disagreements among partners can delay decisions and harm business operations."],
      ["Scenario: Partners disagree on expansion strategy. Risk?", "Conflict may reduce efficiency and threaten profitability."],
      ["What is an advantage regarding taxation?", "Partnerships have pass-through taxation, meaning profits are taxed only at the partners' personal income level."],
      ["Scenario: Partnership earns $100,000 profit. Tax effect?", "Profits taxed once on partners’ personal returns, avoiding corporate-level taxation."],
      ["What is a disadvantage related to continuity?", "Partnership may dissolve if a partner leaves, dies, or withdraws without a plan in place."],
      ["Scenario: Partner retires. What happens to the partnership?", "Partnership may need to be reorganized or dissolved unless agreement provides continuity."],
      ["What is an advantage of easier startup?", "Partnerships are relatively simple to establish with less legal paperwork than corporations."],
      ["Scenario: Two friends start a consulting firm. Advantage?", "Quick formation and lower startup costs compared to a corporation."],
      ["Why is trust important in partnerships?", "Partners rely on each other’s integrity and commitment, as personal liability and shared management make cooperation essential."]
