      ["Aging Accounts Receivable", "A method to estimate uncollectible accounts by categorizing receivables based on how long they have been outstanding."],
      ["Percentage of Sales Method", "A method of estimating bad debts by applying a fixed percentage to total credit sales for a period."],
      ["Percentage of Accounts Receivable Method", "A method of estimating uncollectible accounts by applying a percentage to the ending accounts receivable balance."],
      ["Adjusting Entries", "Journal entries made at the end of an accounting period to update account balances before financial statements are prepared."],
      ["Allowance for Doubtful Accounts", "A contra-asset account used to reduce accounts receivable to the amount expected to be collected."],
      ["Bad Debt Expense", "An expense recognized for accounts receivable that are expected to be uncollectible."],
      ["Accounts Receivable", "Amounts owed to a company by customers for goods or services sold on credit."],
      ["Notes Receivable", "A written promise that a customer will pay a fixed amount on a specific future date."],
      ["Notes Payable", "A written promise to pay a specific amount on a specified date, usually including interest."],
      ["Principal", "The original amount of money borrowed or lent, excluding interest."],
      ["Interest", "The cost of borrowing money or the income earned on lending money, usually expressed as a percentage."],
      ["Maturity Date", "The date when a note payable or receivable must be fully paid."],
      ["Journalizing Notes Receivable", "Recording the issuance, interest earned, and collection of a note in the accounting journal."],
      ["Journalizing Notes Payable", "Recording the issuance, interest incurred, and payment of a note in the accounting journal."],
      ["Accrued Interest", "Interest that has been earned or incurred but not yet paid or received."],
      ["Real-Life Example: Aging Receivables", "Classifying a 60-day-old invoice separately from a 30-day-old invoice to estimate likely bad debts."],
      ["Real-Life Example: Percentage of Sales", "If a company has $50,000 in credit sales and expects 2% will be uncollectible, the bad debt expense is $1,000."],
      ["Real-Life Example: Percentage of Accounts Receivable", "If accounts receivable is $20,000 and 5% is estimated uncollectible, allowance for doubtful accounts is $1,000."],
      ["Example: Notes Receivable", "A customer signs a $5,000, 6% note due in 90 days; the company will record the note and earn interest over 90 days."],
      ["Example: Notes Payable", "A company borrows $10,000 with a 5% 6-month note; it records the note and interest expense over the loan term."],
      ["Calculating Interest", "Interest = Principal × Rate × Time, where time is usually in years."],
      ["Recording Payment of Notes Receivable", "Debit Cash and credit Notes Receivable and Interest Revenue accounts when the note is collected."],
      ["Recording Payment of Notes Payable", "Debit Notes Payable and Interest Expense, credit Cash when the note is paid."],
      ["Adjusting Entry for Bad Debts", "Debit Bad Debt Expense and credit Allowance for Doubtful Accounts to estimate uncollectible amounts."],
      ["Contra-Asset Account", "An account that reduces the balance of a related asset account, like Allowance for Doubtful Accounts reduces Accounts Receivable."],
      ["Example: Adjusting Entry Using Aging Method", "If $1,200 of receivables are over 90 days old and 50% are expected uncollectible, credit $600 to Allowance for Doubtful Accounts."],
      ["Example: Interest Calculation", "A $2,000 note at 6% for 120 days: Interest = $2,000 × 0.06 × (120/360) = $40."],
      ["Recording Accrued Interest", "Debit Interest Receivable and credit Interest Revenue for interest earned but not yet received."],
      ["Recording Accrued Interest Payable", "Debit Interest Expense and credit Interest Payable for interest incurred but not yet paid."],
      ["Purpose of Notes Receivable", "To formalize a promise of payment from a customer, often used for larger or longer-term credit transactions."],
      ["Purpose of Notes Payable", "To formalize a borrowing agreement and specify repayment terms, including interest."],
      ["Example: Collection of Note Receivable", "Receive $1,000 note with $50 interest: debit Cash $1,050, credit Notes Receivable $1,000 and Interest Revenue $50."],
      ["Example: Payment of Note Payable", "Pay $500 note with $25 interest: debit Notes Payable $500, Interest Expense $25, credit Cash $525."],
      ["Recording Partial Payment of Note", "Debit Cash, credit Notes Receivable for principal portion, credit Interest Revenue for interest portion."],
      ["Estimating Bad Debts for Financial Statements", "Helps present accounts receivable at net realizable value on the balance sheet."],
      ["Difference Between Percentage of Sales and Accounts Receivable Method", "Percentage of sales focuses on income statement, accounts receivable focuses on balance sheet."],
      ["Adjusting Entries Timing", "Made at the end of the accounting period before financial statements are prepared."],
      ["Interest Rate", "The percentage applied to principal to determine interest amount."],
      ["Term of Note", "The length of time from issuance to maturity date of a note."],
      ["Recording Dishonored Note", "Debit Accounts Receivable and credit Notes Receivable if the customer fails to pay the note."],
      ["Example: Dishonored Note", "A $1,000 note not paid: debit Accounts Receivable $1,000, credit Notes Receivable $1,000."],
      ["Cash Basis vs Accrual Basis for Notes", "Accrual records interest when earned/incurred, cash basis records when cash is exchanged."],
      ["Example: Allowance for Doubtful Accounts Adjustment", "Current allowance is $400; estimate is $500, debit Bad Debt Expense $100, credit Allowance $100."],
      ["Recording a Note Issued to a Bank", "Debit Cash, credit Notes Payable for the amount borrowed."],
      ["Example: Note Issued to Bank", "Borrow $10,000, 8% 6-month note: Debit Cash $10,000, Credit Notes Payable $10,000."],
      ["Recognizing Interest on a Note", "Debit Interest Receivable or Expense, credit Interest Revenue or Payable as appropriate."],
      ["Example: Interest on Note Receivable", "Note $5,000 at 6% for 1 year: interest earned = $5,000 × 0.06 × 1 = $300."],
      ["Example: Interest on Note Payable", "Borrow $8,000 at 5% for 6 months: interest expense = $8,000 × 0.05 × 0.5 = $200."],
      ["Journalizing Notes in General Ledger", "Post notes receivable/payable, interest, and adjustments to the appropriate ledger accounts."],
      ["Example: Adjusting Entry Using Percentage of Sales", "Credit 2% of $100,000 sales = $2,000 to Allowance for Doubtful Accounts."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Business Lending Money", "A small business lends $2,000 to a customer using a note to ensure repayment with interest."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Borrowing for Equipment", "A company signs a note payable for $20,000 to purchase new machinery, recording interest over the term."],
      ["Example: End-of-Period Adjustment", "Adjust for $150 accrued interest on a note receivable: debit Interest Receivable $150, credit Interest Revenue $150."],
      ["Example: Estimating Bad Debts End of Month", "Accounts receivable total $50,000; aging analysis estimates $3,000 uncollectible: debit Bad Debt Expense $3,000, credit Allowance $3,000."],
      ["Practical Use: Notes vs Accounts Receivable", "Notes receivable provide legal enforceability and interest income, while accounts receivable are simpler but riskier."],
      ["Practical Use: Notes Payable vs Accounts Payable", "Notes payable formalize borrowing with interest and maturity, accounts payable are short-term trade obligations."],
      ["Example: Recording Payment with Partial Interest", "Pay $1,000 note with $30 interest: debit Notes Payable $1,000, Interest Expense $30, credit Cash $1,030."],
      ["Example: Combining Methods", "Use aging method to estimate bad debts for balance sheet, percentage of sales to record bad debt expense on income statement."]
