      ["Prepaid Expenses", "Expenses paid in advance that are recorded as assets until they are incurred."],
      ["Accrued Expenses", "Expenses that have been incurred but not yet paid or recorded."],
      ["Unearned Revenue", "Cash received before goods or services have been delivered, recorded as a liability."],
      ["Accrued Revenue", "Revenue that has been earned but not yet received or recorded."],
      ["Adjusting Entries", "Journal entries made at the end of an accounting period to update account balances."],
      ["Reversing Entries", "Optional journal entries made at the beginning of a new period to simplify recording of subsequent transactions."],
      ["Depreciation Expense", "The allocation of the cost of a long-term asset over its useful life, often adjusted monthly."],
      ["Supplies Expense Adjustment", "An adjusting entry to reflect the amount of supplies used during the period."],
      ["Insurance Expense Adjustment", "Adjusting prepaid insurance to reflect the portion that has expired."],
      ["Salaries Payable", "An accrued expense representing salaries owed to employees but not yet paid."],
      ["Interest Payable", "An accrued expense representing interest owed but not yet paid."],
      ["Revenue Recognition", "The principle that revenue is recognized when earned, regardless of cash receipt."],
      ["Matching Principle", "The accounting principle requiring that expenses be matched with the revenues they help generate."],
      ["Budgeting", "The process of planning future business operations by estimating revenues, expenses, and cash flows."],
      ["Cash Flow", "The inflows and outflows of cash during a period, showing liquidity."],
      ["Operating Budget", "A budget that projects revenues and expenses related to daily operations."],
      ["Capital Budget", "A budget that plans for acquisition of long-term assets like equipment and facilities."],
      ["Revenue Projection", "An estimate of future revenues based on historical data and expected trends."],
      ["Expenditure Projection", "An estimate of future expenses for operations and capital investments."],
      ["Trend Analysis", "Reviewing historical financial data to predict future performance and guide budgeting."],
      ["Priorities in Budgeting", "Identifying which expenses and investments are most critical for achieving goals."],
      ["Example: Prepaid Rent Adjustment", "A company prepays $12,000 for a year; each month, $1,000 is recorded as rent expense."],
      ["Example: Accrued Salaries", "Employees earned $5,000 in December but will be paid in January; adjust December with Salaries Expense $5,000 and Salaries Payable $5,000."],
      ["Example: Unearned Revenue Adjustment", "A customer prepays $2,400 for a one-year service; monthly, $200 is recognized as revenue."],
      ["Example: Accrued Interest Revenue", "Interest earned on a note of $1,000 at 6% for 2 months: $10, adjust with Interest Receivable $10 and Interest Revenue $10."],
      ["Example: Reversing Entry", "Debit Salaries Payable and credit Salaries Expense to simplify recording January payroll."],
      ["Cash Budget", "A budget showing expected cash inflows and outflows to ensure sufficient liquidity."],
      ["Example: Cash Flow Scenario", "A company expects $50,000 inflow from sales and $30,000 outflow for expenses, net increase $20,000."],
      ["Example: Insurance Prepaid Adjustment", "Prepaid insurance $1,200 for 12 months; monthly adjustment: debit Insurance Expense $100, credit Prepaid Insurance $100."],
      ["Example: Supplies Adjustment", "Beginning supplies $500, ending supplies $200: Supplies Expense $300, credit Supplies $300."],
      ["Accrual Basis Accounting", "Recording revenues and expenses when earned or incurred, not when cash changes hands."],
      ["Example: Accrued Utilities Expense", "Utility bill $600 for December received in January: debit Utilities Expense $600, credit Utilities Payable $600."],
      ["Depreciation Adjusting Entry", "Debit Depreciation Expense and credit Accumulated Depreciation for the period."],
      ["Example: Revenue Recognition Adjustment", "Service performed in December but cash received in January: debit Accounts Receivable, credit Service Revenue."],
      ["Purpose of Reversing Entries", "To avoid double counting expenses or revenues and simplify bookkeeping in the new period."],
      ["Example: Reversing Accrued Interest", "Reverse December interest accrued: debit Interest Revenue, credit Interest Receivable; record cash in January."],
      ["Step in Budget Preparation: Review Revenues", "Analyze past revenues and trends to estimate future income."],
      ["Step in Budget Preparation: Review Expenditures", "Analyze past expenses and necessary future costs for operations."],
      ["Step in Budget Preparation: Identify Trends", "Evaluate patterns in sales, costs, and cash flow to inform projections."],
      ["Step in Budget Preparation: Set Priorities", "Determine which projects or expenses are critical to fund."],
      ["Step in Budget Preparation: Make Projections", "Forecast future revenues, expenses, and cash needs for the period."],
      ["Example: Operating Budget Projection", "Estimate $100,000 revenue, $60,000 expenses, net operating income $40,000."],
      ["Example: Capital Budget Projection", "Plan $50,000 for new equipment purchase next quarter."],
      ["Example: Adjusting Unearned Revenue", "Received $1,200 for annual subscription; recognize $100 per month as revenue."],
      ["Example: Reversing Prepaid Expenses", "Reverse prior period prepaid rent adjustment to simplify new period rent payment recording."],
      ["Example: Budget Cash Flow Review", "Projected inflow $80,000, outflow $70,000, net cash $10,000; ensures sufficient liquidity."],
      ["Example: Accrued Revenue Entry", "Provided services worth $500 not yet billed: debit Accounts Receivable $500, credit Service Revenue $500."],
      ["Example: Prioritizing Budget Items", "Critical expenses: payroll and utilities; non-essential: marketing campaign increase."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Seasonal Revenue", "Company adjusts budget to expect higher sales in December and lower in January."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Accrued Bonus", "Employee bonus earned in December but paid in February: record as accrued expense."],
      ["Practical Tip: Reversing Entries", "Helps avoid complicated double entries when actual payment or receipt occurs in new period."],
      ["Practical Tip: Cash Flow Management", "Regularly review projected inflows/outflows to prevent shortfalls."],
      ["Real-Life Example: Supplies Usage", "Company buys $1,000 of supplies; $600 used by month-end: adjusting entry to reflect expense."],
      ["Example: Multi-Month Prepaid Expense", "Prepaid $3,000 for 3-month software license: monthly expense $1,000."],
      ["Example: Budget Trend Analysis", "Sales increasing 5% per year; budget next year 5% higher than current year."],
      ["Example: Adjusting Accrued Revenue", "Consulting services performed $1,500 but not invoiced: debit Accounts Receivable, credit Revenue $1,500."],
      ["Example: Reversing Accrued Expenses", "Reverse accrued salaries of $2,000 from previous month: debit Salaries Payable, credit Salaries Expense $2,000."],
      ["Example: Budgeting for Priorities", "Allocate limited funds first to operations, then to expansion or marketing."],
      ["Example: Unearned Revenue Scenario", "Customer prepays $600 for a 6-month gym membership: recognize $100 revenue monthly."],
      ["Example: Accrued Tax Expense", "Taxes owed $800 for December but paid in January: debit Tax Expense $800, credit Tax Payable $800."]
