      ["Master Budget", "A comprehensive financial plan that combines all individual budgets into one overall budget for a period."],
      ["Flexible Budget", "A budget that adjusts projected costs and revenues based on the actual level of activity."],
      ["Performance Report", "A report that compares budgeted amounts to actual amounts to evaluate management performance."],
      ["Budget Variance", "The difference between budgeted and actual amounts."],
      ["Revenue Variance", "The difference between budgeted revenue and actual revenue."],
      ["Expense Variance", "The difference between budgeted expense and actual expense."],
      ["Operating Budget", "A budget that details expected revenues and expenses for day-to-day operations."],
      ["Capital Budget", "A budget that plans for acquisition and financing of long-term assets."],
      ["Static Budget", "A fixed budget prepared for a single level of activity, not adjusted for actual activity."],
      ["Sales Volume Variance", "The difference in budgeted and actual revenue caused by a change in quantity sold."],
      ["Flexible Budget Variance", "The difference between actual results and the flexible budget, reflecting efficiency and cost control."],
      ["Budget Preparation", "The process of estimating revenues, expenses, and other financial data for a future period."],
      ["Cost Center", "A department or unit within an organization that incurs costs but does not directly generate revenue."],
      ["Profit Center", "A department or unit that generates revenue and is responsible for its own profit."],
      ["Revenue Center", "A department responsible for generating sales revenue."],
      ["Example: Master Budget", "Combines sales, production, direct materials, direct labor, overhead, and cash budgets into one plan."],
      ["Example: Flexible Budget", "If actual production is 1,200 units instead of 1,000 units, the flexible budget adjusts costs accordingly."],
      ["Example: Performance Report", "Actual sales $50,000 vs budgeted $45,000; report highlights $5,000 favorable variance."],
      ["Direct Materials Budget", "Estimates the quantity and cost of materials needed for production."],
      ["Direct Labor Budget", "Estimates labor hours and cost needed for production."],
      ["Manufacturing Overhead Budget", "Estimates all production overhead costs, including fixed and variable components."],
      ["Selling and Administrative Expense Budget", "Estimates non-production costs such as marketing, sales, and administration."],
      ["Cash Budget", "Projects cash inflows and outflows to ensure adequate liquidity for operations."],
      ["Example: Revenue Variance", "Budgeted sales $100,000; actual sales $95,000; unfavorable variance $5,000."],
      ["Example: Expense Variance", "Budgeted expenses $40,000; actual $38,000; favorable variance $2,000."],
      ["Example: Sales Volume Variance", "Budgeted 500 units; sold 550 units; variance reflects additional revenue from higher sales."],
      ["Example: Flexible Budget Adjustment", "Variable costs increase proportionally with actual output, fixed costs remain unchanged."],
      ["Example: Budget Variance Analysis", "Compare master budget to actual results to identify areas needing management attention."],
      ["Purpose of Flexible Budgets", "To provide a more accurate basis for performance evaluation by adjusting for actual activity levels."],
      ["Purpose of Master Budget", "To provide a comprehensive plan that integrates all areas of operations and finance."],
      ["Zero-Based Budgeting", "A budgeting method where every expense must be justified for each new period, starting from zero."],
      ["Incremental Budgeting", "A budgeting method where the previous period's budget is used as a base and adjusted for changes."],
      ["Standard Cost", "A predetermined cost of producing a product or service, used for budgeting and variance analysis."],
      ["Example: Direct Materials Flexible Budget", "Budgeted cost per unit $5, actual units 1,200, total budgeted cost $6,000."],
      ["Example: Direct Labor Flexible Budget", "Standard labor cost $10/unit, actual units 1,200, flexible budget cost $12,000."],
      ["Example: Manufacturing Overhead Flexible Budget", "Variable overhead $2/unit, fixed $5,000, actual 1,200 units: total $7,400."],
      ["Example: Cash Budget Scenario", "Beginning cash $10,000; inflows $50,000; outflows $45,000; ending cash $15,000."],
      ["Example: Profit Center Performance", "Compare actual profit to budgeted profit to evaluate department performance."],
      ["Example: Cost Center Performance", "Compare actual costs to budgeted costs to monitor efficiency."],
      ["Example: Revenue Center Performance", "Compare actual revenue to budgeted revenue to monitor sales performance."],
      ["Performance Evaluation", "Using budgeted vs actual comparisons to assess efficiency, cost control, and profitability."],
      ["Variance Analysis", "Analyzing differences between budgeted and actual results to understand reasons for discrepancies."],
      ["Flexible vs Static Budget", "Flexible adjusts for actual activity; static does not, making flexible more useful for performance evaluation."],
      ["Example: Favorable Variance", "Actual expense $8,000 vs budget $10,000; $2,000 favorable variance."],
      ["Example: Unfavorable Variance", "Actual revenue $45,000 vs budget $50,000; $5,000 unfavorable variance."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Seasonal Production", "Flexible budget adjusts raw material and labor costs for higher holiday season production."],
      ["Real-Life Scenario: Unexpected Sales", "Performance report shows variance; management can analyze causes and adjust operations."],
      ["Practical Tip: Master Budget Use", "Provides overall planning, sets targets, and coordinates activities across departments."],
      ["Practical Tip: Flexible Budget Use", "Assesses efficiency by comparing actual results to what should have occurred at actual activity levels."],
      ["Example: Combining Master and Flexible Budgets", "Use master budget for planning, flexible budget for performance evaluation."],
      ["Example: Overhead Variance Analysis", "Actual overhead $15,000, flexible budget $14,000; $1,000 unfavorable variance."],
      ["Example: Sales Trend Performance", "Budgeted sales growth 5%, actual 7%; favorable revenue variance."],
      ["Example: Adjusting Budget Mid-Year", "Flexible budget can be recalculated if significant changes in activity occur."],
      ["Example: Master Budget Coordination", "Sales, production, and cash budgets integrated to ensure consistent planning."],
      ["Example: Expense Control", "Compare actual expenses to flexible budget to identify inefficiencies."],
      ["Example: Management Decision Making", "Use performance reports and variances to make strategic operational decisions."],
      ["Example: Capital Budget Flexible Review", "Actual equipment costs exceed budget; flexible budget highlights variance."],
      ["Example: Inventory Cost Variance", "Flexible budget shows increase in raw material costs due to higher production."],
      ["Example: Real-Life Small Business", "Owner prepares master budget to plan for entire year, flexible budget helps track actual sales and costs."],
      ["Example: Forecasting Future Budgets", "Use variance analysis from performance reports to improve next period's master budget."]
